transcript_text: If you're trying to add some width to your back, then you need to be doing the half-neeling  lap pull down.  Nothing hammers the lats like this.  I already did a video on this exercise, but I wanted to provide a comparison to better  illustrate my point.  Firstly, this arm angle is in line with the muscle fibers of the lats, and it keeps the  scapula protracted in your arm in front of you, which means the lat is working relatively  independently.  Secondly, the movement is initiated with the upper arm, not the scapula, so it is effectively  entirely a lat movement.  Anything that involves bringing the humerus to upper arm toward the body against resistance  will recruit the lat, but that's not the same thing as isolating the lats with  which is definitely worth your time if you're trying to build a teenage mutant interturtle  back.  The lat doesn't do as much once your elbow is behind your body like with the traditional  pull-down scene here.  At this point, muscles like the terries, lower traps, and wrong boards are bearing most  of the resistance.
